Several things I'm not sure about in this article.

1. A D-class who's crime was vandalism. It is my understanding that D-class are typically people who have committed heinous crimes such as rape, murder, etc. After all the D stands for  and if someone is supposed to get out of jail any time soon, they aren't really disposable.

2.  is typically used in articles to qualify something that is hard to calculate precisely, like a percentage of surface area, something so massive in number that it is hard to count (much more numborous than 7), or something that changes quantity anomalously but tends to float around one state in particular.

3. Bitterroot national Forest is a fairly large place, at 6,423 that sounds a bit wrong. Surely a place so large does not just have 1 entrance.

4. The dialogue between D-class and researcher is very sparse. D-class goes all the way to the state border (without being told to) and doesn't say anything to the researcher the whole time. Not only this but we aren't even told that some dialogue may be removed for brevity, so the audio version of this logue would be majority silence as no-one talks for some reason.







